    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p><bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>181</citedRange> (diplomatic transcription from Cassels' notebooks)</bibl>;
                <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>121000</citedRange></bibl>.
                Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#cassels1955"/>, p. <citedRange>41</citedRange></bibl> (mention of a marble base);
                    <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.47</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ἁγησίδικος">Ἁγησίδικ<unclear>ο</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Παραιβάτας" type="patronymic">Παραιβάτα</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p><app loc="1"><lem>Ἁγησίδικ<unclear>ο</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied></lem>
                <rdg resp="#dthorn-thorn2009" hand="Cassels">ΑΓΗΣΙΔΙΚΩ <note>Cassels' Grey Book</note></rdg></app></p>
                
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Hagèsidikos fils de Paraibatas.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Hagesidikos son of Paraibatas.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Hagesidikos figlio di Paraibatas.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>Although compound names in <foreign xml:lang="grc"> Ἁγησ(ι)-</foreign> are numerous in Cyrenaica, this one was hitherto unattested. On the contrary, the father's name, 
                   <foreign xml:lang="grc">Παραιβάτας</foreign> is one of the most typical names of Cyrenaica. It is thus impossible to relate the deceased with any known family.</p>
	           <p>As names of the deceased on bases are always at the nominative case, we suppose that Cassels copied erroneously an ending with omega, which would be the genitive.</p>
	           <p>For the date, we follow Cassesl' opinion.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
